  <mainDescription>&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Purpose&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    This metric is used in the following purposes:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        as an indicator of product quality;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        helping priorities and planing work;&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        predicting problems after shipment.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Monitor Defect Backlog to&amp;nbsp;avoid the accumulation of a large number of defects. Left unresolved, defects can&#xD;
    significantly impact the project with increased cost the later they are addressed in the lifecycle. At the time of&#xD;
    customer ship, this metric helps the team understand how many defects customers are likely to find that have already&#xD;
    been identified in the development lifecycle.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Definition&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Count: the number of open defects at a point in time&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Group by defect status.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Analysis&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Monitor the Defect Backlog over time using a line chart. Plot units of time on the X axis and the number of defects in&#xD;
    the backlog on the Y axis. A drill down report is helpful to see open defects with their associated component.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The defect backlog should be kept at a reasonable level.&amp;nbsp; Targets based on past experience are helpful as are&#xD;
    release to release comparisons. The trend over time should significantly decrease as the product approaches&#xD;
    its&amp;nbsp;release target date.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    A high number of defects in the backlog will begin to impact the team's velocity as defects are addressed. The team&#xD;
    should ensure that defects are removed as&amp;nbsp;soon &amp;nbsp;as is possible (and practical) to the point of insertion when&#xD;
    rework is less costly. If the number of defects in the backlog is high near the end of the lifecycle, the team will&#xD;
    likely be integrating many fixes at the last minute which could be a predictor of future quality problems.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Releasing a product with a&amp;nbsp;large Defect Backlog is likely to negatively impact customer satisfaction. It is also&#xD;
    an indication of the effort that will be required&amp;nbsp;to remove defects post-ship.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Below is an example of a Defect Backlog report, which shows the number of defects for the Smarter Planet Online Auction&#xD;
    project. Notice the trend of an increasing number of open defects near the end of the reporting period.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &lt;img alt=&quot;Defect Backlog report&quot; src=&quot;resources/defect_backlog.gif&quot; width=&quot;420&quot; height=&quot;344&quot; />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Frequency and reporting&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The team reviews the defect backlog during iteration planning to help prioritize their&amp;nbsp;work.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;Management&#xD;
    monitors Defect Backlog&amp;nbsp;trends&amp;nbsp;throughout the release and across releases.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;h3>&#xD;
    Collection and reporting tools&#xD;
&lt;/h3>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    &amp;nbsp;IBM&amp;reg; Rational&amp;reg; ClearQuest&amp;reg;, IBM&amp;reg; Rational&amp;reg; Team Concert&amp;reg;&amp;nbsp; and IBM&amp;reg; Rational&amp;reg; Quality&#xD;
    Manager&amp;reg;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;collect&amp;nbsp;Defect Backlog data.&amp;nbsp;IBM&amp;reg; Rational&amp;reg; Insight&amp;reg; reports on this metric.&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
